		</table></td><td class="PanelBodyAlternate" valign="Top"><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3" border="0" width="100%">
			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: What is wrong with these young bards today?<a name="4684"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Feb 22 03 2:13 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>As I've said lots in the past, I'm a grouping bard by nature.  I'd swarm and chant kite more than I do if only my pathetic connection didn't drop me just about every time I set out to solo.
<br />

<br />
That said, I've never encountered problems with keeping my skills up to par (although I did have a minor ordeal or two raising brass when I first got it).  I have, however, run into entirely too many lowbie bards who don't know what they're doing (on my alts and when watching lowbie RL friends of mine play).  Most of these can be taught to twist, etc., however, and I don't mind helping 'em out.  What I -do- get irritable about is when I am grouped with a bard (on one of my alts) who knows how to twist but refuses to do it on the basis that &quot;low level songs suck.&quot;
<br />

<br />
In other words, he/she turns on Hymn of Restoration and melees without singing/playing anything else, despite knowing that twisting Anthem de Arms, Hymn, and maybe Jaxon's would aid the group considerably more while giving him/her good practice for twisting.
<br />

<br />
I guess what I'm trying say here is that I don't see how bards who refuse to work at playing the class at low levels expect to be able to play the class well at high levels, especially in a group situation where one has to know exactly what songs to twist and in what order to make the most of a given group setup.
<br />

<br />
I am proud of any bard who will work at the class and experiment with various twists in an attempt to figure out what songs best fit the situation and group type, and I don't mind if their twists fall apart due to lag factors (like my own on occasion), but lazy bards get on my nerves.  Thank goodness all of the bards in my current guild (we have more than a guild on my server usually has) are intelligent, hardoworking bards.  <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-1.gif" border="0" alt="Smiley" hspace="2" /> </span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="SmallText"><hr size="1" align="left" width="15%">Melees love us for the haste; casters love us for the mana; fleeing loonies love us for the Selo's.<br>
---Bard Motto<br>
<a href=http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=910907>Lenowill's Magelo profile</a></span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td height="2"></td>
